8. Array & Map Functions-They’re extremely useful when working with nested or complex data structures
    array allows column to store array of elements of the same data type
	
-  explode() – flatten arrays
   df=df.withColumn('Tags',explode(col('Tags')))
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-  explode_outer() - it preserves null and empty arrays instead of dropping them.
   df=df.withColumn('Tags',explode_outer(col('Tags')))
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-  pos_explode() - in PySpark is like explode(), but it also gives you the position (index) of each element
   in the array along with the element itself.
   df=df.withColumn('Tags',posexplode(col('Tags)))
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
-  size() – length of array
   df=df.withColumn('length',size(col('Tags')))
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- map_keys()- → Returns an array of all keys in the map, map_values() – → Returns an array of all values in the map.
  
  df.withColumn('Keys',map_keys(col('col1')))
  df.withColumn('values',map_values(col('col1')))
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-  array()
   df=df.withColumn('full_name',array(col('first_name'),col('last_name')))
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- array_contains()
   df=df.filter(array_contains(col('col1'),'shaik'))
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
